            {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Perfect! I have the answer. Here are the available fields in the hook input JSON for those hook events:\n\n## Hook Input Fields\n\nAll four hook types you're asking about receive these **common fields via stdin**:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"session_id\": \"abc123\",\n  \"transcript_path\": \"/path/to/transcript.jsonl\",\n  \"cwd\": \"/current/working/directory\",\n  \"permission_mode\": \"default|plan|acceptEdits|auto|dontAsk|bypassPermissions\",\n  \"hook_event_name\": \"EventName\"\n}\n```\n\n### Yes, `session_id` is available in all hooks\n\nYou can absolutely scope guardrails to the session that started a workflow using the `session_id` field.\n\n### Hook-specific additional fields:\n\n**PreToolUse**:\n- `tool_name` (Bash, Edit, Write, Read, etc.)\n- `tool_input` (tool-specific parameters)\n- `tool_use_id` (unique identifier)\n\n**PostToolUse**:\n- `tool_name`\n- `tool_input`\n- `tool_response` (tool result)\n- `tool_use_id`\n\n**SubagentStop**:\n- `stop_hook_active` (boolean)\n- `agent_id` (unique identifier for the subagent)\n- `agent_type` (agent name like \"Explore\", \"Plan\", etc.)\n- `agent_transcript_path` (path to subagent transcript)\n- `last_assistant_message` (final response text)\n\n**Stop**:\n- No additional tool-specific fields (just the common fields)\n\nThis means you can track workflow-specific guardrail state by storing it indexed by `session_id`, and guardrails will only apply to actions within that session. This is a perfect pattern for your needs."
